1
00:00:01,820 --> 00:00:12,632
Tonight's talk continues with the teaching known as the raft which describes someone following a path that leads to a shore that is perilous owing to a great expanse of water.

2
00:00:13,835 --> 00:00:17,518
Across the water he sees another shore where the ground is secure.

3
00:00:18,661 --> 00:00:27,692
He gathers grass, twigs, branches and leaves, binds them together to make a raft and paddling energetically crosses the flood.

4
00:00:29,527 --> 00:00:36,600
The near shore, if you remember, stands for self-identity, while the far shore represents freedom.

5
00:00:38,024 --> 00:00:53,072
Ultimately, this means the complete freedom of Nibbana, but for the purpose of this sutta, we're best to think of the far shore as those temporary periods of freedom that emerge when we've worked our way mindfully through some struggle.

6
00:00:54,959 --> 00:01:00,628
The water refers to the four floods which represent those aspects of life we identify with.

7
00:01:01,569 --> 00:01:06,036
Sensuality, becoming, views and ignorance.

8
00:01:07,659 --> 00:01:18,114
On the near shore we are unwittingly taking on a false identity and will suffer on account of that because sooner or later this identity will be threatened.

9
00:01:20,896 --> 00:01:24,402
Last night we looked at the floods of sensuality and views.

10
00:01:25,364 --> 00:01:29,230
Tonight we look at the other floods, starting with the flood of becoming.

11
00:01:31,093 --> 00:01:35,480
This flood relates to our identity as a person with a future and a past.

12
00:01:36,724 --> 00:01:43,275
It's especially connected with our roles as parent, daughter, technician, cook and so on.

13
00:01:44,385 --> 00:01:53,254
More subtly, we also assume social roles such as respectable person, good friend, social activist, etc.

14
00:01:54,617 --> 00:01:58,801
We're not fully aware of some of our roles or consciously choosing to play them.

15
00:01:59,843 --> 00:02:06,590
For example, we can play victim roles in certain circumstances when we don't know how to cope with misfortune.

16
00:02:07,870 --> 00:02:13,396
At other times, we play the role of bully in an attempt to control ourselves or others.

17
00:02:13,816 --> 00:02:20,615
In other circumstances, we'll end up playing roles of mother hen, wise owl, grumpy grouse.

18
00:02:21,818 --> 00:02:26,069
We have a whole menagerie inside us, waiting for their moment on stage.

19
00:02:29,425 --> 00:02:37,355
Just as sensuality and views can play meaningful, beneficial parts in our lives, our roles can also serve us well.

20
00:02:38,478 --> 00:02:46,248
They give us predictable ways of interacting with others which simplifies social situations and lets us all work together well.

21
00:02:47,390 --> 00:02:53,239
The problem only comes when we forget that these roles are temporary and contingent.

22
00:02:54,181 --> 00:03:02,973
There will come a time when they are not appropriate and unless we can let go we will suffer and so also will our relationships.

23
00:03:04,436 --> 00:03:07,740
Retirement for example is a challenge for most people.

24
00:03:08,942 --> 00:03:15,050
Our role as electrician or teacher or secretary which we knew so well is suddenly gone.

25
00:03:16,012 --> 00:03:19,497
We don't know who we are anymore or what to do with ourselves.

26
00:03:21,198 --> 00:03:26,264
As children turn into adults, we find it difficult to let go of parent-child roles.

27
00:03:29,710 --> 00:03:31,832
Why is this flood termed becoming?

28
00:03:33,213 --> 00:03:35,518
Why not call it the flood of roles?

29
00:03:37,479 --> 00:03:42,306
If we're looking back on our role as teacher or parent, that isn't a problem.

30
00:03:43,247 --> 00:03:49,736
It's a way of understanding and appreciating our lives, learning from past mistakes and forgiving these.

31
00:03:50,998 --> 00:03:56,486
It's only the projection of that role into the future that gets us swept off our feet.

32
00:03:57,949 --> 00:04:01,394
The energetic pull of the flood is towards the future.

33
00:04:02,455 --> 00:04:06,762
So becoming describes the feeling tone of this flood very well.

34
00:04:06,801 --> 00:04:15,814
Retirement and other major role changes in life are strong currents in the flood of becoming.

35
00:04:17,478 --> 00:04:20,382
But we get swept away in small ways every day.

36
00:04:21,677 --> 00:04:29,711
We can use each of these smaller floods as opportunities to practice making a raft and getting safely to the far shore.

37
00:04:31,653 --> 00:04:37,663
In meditation, how often do we get carried away into a fantasy about how wonderful we are?

38
00:04:39,146 --> 00:04:45,357
It might be that we're going to write the most spectacular novel worthy of a hundred Man Booker prizes.

39
00:04:46,180 --> 00:04:53,492
In another meditation, we'd be climbing Mount Everest without oxygen, winning Wimbledon, awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.

40
00:04:55,293 --> 00:04:58,319
These are mini tsunamis in the flood of becoming.

41
00:04:59,942 --> 00:05:05,269
Instead of condemning yourself for these, see how well you can stay afloat in their midst.

42
00:05:07,874 --> 00:05:10,298
Body awareness makes a great raft.

43
00:05:11,526 --> 00:05:19,937
The mind can be sparking with ideas on how we will impress the world, but the body is sitting there in meditation, grounding us.

44
00:05:22,120 --> 00:05:27,726
In my experience, this flood seems to be pulling me towards a very pleasant, enticing future.

45
00:05:28,749 --> 00:05:33,855
This imagined future would be reflected in my body as pleasant sensations.

46
00:05:34,814 --> 00:05:51,913
If I can locate and hold attention on those sensations, the sparky thoughts and ideas fade and I get a better sense of the energies surging around my body, generating all those pleasant sensations which my mind is interpreting as a wonderful future.

47
00:05:53,276 --> 00:05:59,944
At times, then, I might be persuaded to relax a bit, enjoy the pleasure in the here and now.

48
00:06:02,927 --> 00:06:09,360
As I relax, I might detect a couple of separate strands to the energies flowing around my body.

49
00:06:11,345 --> 00:06:14,630
At one level, there is self-care, metta.

50
00:06:15,774 --> 00:06:22,927
A kindly streak within me is quietly generating pleasant sensations as an expression of care.

51
00:06:24,324 --> 00:06:31,435
Then there are the energies driven by desire, clutching onto the pleasure, embroidering a magnificent future out of it.

52
00:06:32,677 --> 00:06:41,331
Although I'm strongly attached to this aspect of the experience, I have to admit that the light of awareness shows it up as painful, stressful.

53
00:06:42,593 --> 00:06:51,125
Essentially, I'm rejecting the pleasure being offered by my meta-streak, saying, this isn't worth anything, what I need is a great future.

54
00:06:54,110 --> 00:07:02,000
If I can sit with the emotions and feelings generated within this flood of becoming, I'm undermining the delusion at its core.

55
00:07:03,521 --> 00:07:12,254
This person I'm so identified with, the soon-to-be Nobel Prize Peace Winner, can I find that person here and now?

56
00:07:14,076 --> 00:07:18,843
Are they in my chest, my stomach, my throat, my face?

57
00:07:20,764 --> 00:07:23,509
From afar it seems the answer is yes.

58
00:07:24,129 --> 00:07:29,076
I might find a hot spot in my throat, for example, where that wonderful person resides.

59
00:07:30,557 --> 00:07:39,269
But when I look closely, all I find are physical sensations, pleasant feelings and the deep displeasure of confusion.

60
00:07:41,232 --> 00:07:43,134
Where did that wonderful person escape to?

61
00:07:44,636 --> 00:07:46,137
Why can't I pin them down?

62
00:07:48,716 --> 00:07:56,285
By now, awareness has penetrated the flood of becoming deep enough to be exploring the underlying flood of ignorance.

63
00:07:57,646 --> 00:08:05,673
Caught up in the delusion of self, I'm looking for my essence as something objective that I can know, discern, pinpoint.

64
00:08:07,596 --> 00:08:17,526
But I have to admit, sadly, that everything I know keeps dissolving, changing, become other than whatever it seemed to be a moment ago.

65
00:08:19,057 --> 00:08:21,040
All very unsatisfactory.

66
00:08:22,442 --> 00:08:25,406
Sooner or later, I give up on the futile search.

67
00:08:26,548 --> 00:08:32,017
With luck, I'll surrender, for even a few blessed moments, to the truth of Anatta.

68
00:08:33,038 --> 00:08:40,109
No longer interested in defining myself as an essential separation from the rest of experience.

69
00:08:40,129 --> 00:08:40,789
What a relief.

70
00:08:41,892 --> 00:08:43,934
A toehold on the far shore.

71
00:08:46,767 --> 00:08:59,504
I'll say a bit more about the flood of delusion later on but for now I want to come back to the flood of becoming and your daydreams about the wonderful person you truly are if only the rest of the world would wake up and take notice.

72
00:09:01,447 --> 00:09:10,558
I'm not encouraging you to daydream but to let the raft of Vipassana bob up and down on the waves of this flood as you paddle your way to the far shore.

73
00:09:13,163 --> 00:09:16,167
Let's look at a potential tsunami from daily life.

74
00:09:17,446 --> 00:09:21,650
Suppose you're a geography teacher standing in front of a class of teenagers.

75
00:09:22,552 --> 00:09:28,019
Some of them are listening, some look bored and abstracted, while a group in the back are laughing and chatting.

76
00:09:29,159 --> 00:09:31,643
You call for silence, but they ignore you.

77
00:09:32,364 --> 00:09:35,869
Jack, stop talking and pay attention, you call to the ringleader.

78
00:09:36,909 --> 00:09:41,174
Give me one good reason, sneers Jack, getting a laugh from his buddies.

79
00:09:41,475 --> 00:09:47,143
Okay, leave the class now and go to the headmaster's office, you order sternly.

80
00:09:48,284 --> 00:09:52,671
Come and make me, he retorts, leaning back in his chair defiantly.

81
00:09:53,672 --> 00:09:56,515
Your blood is boiling and you want to murder him.

82
00:09:56,556 --> 00:10:02,923
You're also aware that the class has gone still, with all eyes on you to see your next move.

83
00:10:04,426 --> 00:10:10,774
It's the flood of becoming, resting as always on the flood of ignorance, which is making your blood boil.

84
00:10:11,902 --> 00:10:16,206
you're identified with your role as teacher and it's under severe threat.

85
00:10:17,327 --> 00:10:24,176
If you can't control the situation, the class will lose respect for you and you might also lose confidence in yourself as a teacher.

86
00:10:25,817 --> 00:10:27,379
All this is very real.

87
00:10:27,438 --> 00:10:34,206
But for spiritual practice, we have to be prepared to look underneath the surface reality.

88
00:10:35,368 --> 00:10:41,875
From the spiritual perspective, the danger is that you're being severely tempted to act on anger

89
00:10:44,115 --> 00:10:51,163
Although it can seem counterintuitive, working at the spiritual level can have unexpected benefits at the surface level.

90
00:10:52,706 --> 00:10:59,033
If we can muster goodwill in a challenging situation, others often pick up on this and follow suit.

91
00:11:00,274 --> 00:11:04,821
For the start, though, we have to put aside any desire for specific outcomes.

92
00:11:05,942 --> 00:11:12,789
We have to let all worldly considerations go and give all our heart into gathering bits and pieces for our raft.

93
00:11:14,861 --> 00:11:17,851
mindfulness would be a great starting ingredient.

94
00:11:19,789 --> 00:11:27,298
If you can register your anger and that you're feeling threatened, you will then have some objectivity on the situation.

95
00:11:28,801 --> 00:11:36,931
Some degree of calm would greatly help, so you can feel your feet on the ground for a few seconds or take a mindful breath.

96
00:11:38,113 --> 00:11:45,020
If you can, add in a meta-wish such as, may I handle this situation wisely?

97
00:11:47,346 --> 00:12:00,546
With mindfulness, calm and a degree of metta on board, you may be able to give metta the flavour of equanimity with the wish like, may your behaviour not provoke me to react.

98
00:12:02,327 --> 00:12:07,034
This acknowledges the danger of reactivity within a sentiment of goodwill.

99
00:12:08,417 --> 00:12:10,360
It forms a wide net for metta.

100
00:12:11,160 --> 00:12:14,264
Hopefully your anger will be caught within this.

101
00:12:18,429 --> 00:12:24,658
While none of this changes anything externally, it will have changed things radically within yourself.

102
00:12:26,299 --> 00:12:38,716
The situation has now been encompassed within your Dhamma practice, and no matter what happens next, you will be on board a raft rather than drowning in the sea of becoming.

103
00:12:41,988 --> 00:12:51,517
You've also saved yourself from the worst outcome giving Jack a clatter and possibly getting the sack or maybe even being charged with assault.

104
00:12:53,539 --> 00:13:00,746
Even if you make an utter fool of yourself and get the sack anyway it means teaching teenagers was never going to be your career.

105
00:13:02,708 --> 00:13:11,116
What matters from the spiritual perspective is not whether you get the sack but how you handle that setback if it comes.

106
00:13:14,184 --> 00:13:22,595
Supposing mindfulness, calm and meta got you into some sort of a raft and you feel enough confidence to launch into the flood.

107
00:13:24,356 --> 00:13:41,037
My imagination can't stretch to anything more original than, I can't force you out of the class Jack, but I want you to know that I'm appalled by your behaviour and unless it improves radically, I'll be going to the head myself after class with the full story.

108
00:13:43,649 --> 00:13:52,144
You're afloat for the moment, but need to be paddling constantly in case any retort from Jack causes a wave to topple you back into fury.

109
00:13:54,067 --> 00:13:56,451
So is there anything else that could add buoyancy?

110
00:13:59,736 --> 00:14:08,711
One would be to extend your meta-wishes to Jack and the rest of the class with something like, May we make it through this crisis?

111
00:14:10,750 --> 00:14:18,458
If you have a strong faith you could ask the Buddha or Quan Yin for help or any devas who happen to be nearby.

112
00:14:18,519 --> 00:14:23,063
This would be adding faith and devotion to your raft.

113
00:14:26,868 --> 00:14:33,635
One very powerful Metta practice is to see all beings as enlightened except for ourselves.

114
00:14:35,033 --> 00:14:42,342
Everyone else is playing their roles here on earth with only one purpose in mind, to liberate us from suffering.

115
00:14:43,705 --> 00:14:49,152
Our supposed enemies are only pretending to threaten us in order to sharpen our practice.

116
00:14:50,794 --> 00:14:58,365
If you could manage even a momentary glimpse of that possibility, it could turn the raft into a cruise ship.

117
00:14:58,384 --> 00:15:03,572
No longer are you the teacher, they are the teachers and you are the pupil.

118
00:15:04,732 --> 00:15:12,488
This radical shift in perspective may let you see some humour in the situation and find a creative way to handle it.

119
00:15:15,453 --> 00:15:25,493
But suppose you didn't manage to build any raft and are striding towards the back of the class, intending to catch Jack by the scruff of the neck and give him a good clatter.

120
00:15:26,923 --> 00:15:35,634
If you've been saying the precepts regularly, then the phrase, not to harm living beings, may pop into your head to bring you to a halt.

121
00:15:36,878 --> 00:15:39,668
This would be to start your raft with morality.

122
00:15:41,167 --> 00:15:46,114
Acknowledging the harm intended, you might resolve to find some other way of dealing with the situation.

123
00:15:47,375 --> 00:15:52,062
To borrow Bhante's phrase, a resolute resolution is what's needed here.

124
00:15:52,082 --> 00:15:54,506
I can do no harm.

125
00:15:55,248 --> 00:15:56,710
I ought to do no harm.

126
00:15:57,552 --> 00:15:58,974
I want to do no harm.

127
00:15:58,994 --> 00:16:01,216
I will do no harm.

128
00:16:02,902 --> 00:16:11,453
Resolutions are strengthened by a physical gesture and in this case to turn around and walk slowly back to your desk could fit the bill.

129
00:16:14,038 --> 00:16:19,465
The trouble is that you've already let your emotions escalate as well as heightening the tension in the room.

130
00:16:19,485 --> 00:16:27,897
So there will probably be a strong temptation towards harsh speech as a means of saving face and regaining some control.

131
00:16:29,311 --> 00:16:37,600
Hopefully, you will also remember the precept against wrong speech and start casting around for some wisdom.

132
00:16:37,659 --> 00:16:42,745
Equanimity is a major support at times like these.

133
00:16:44,125 --> 00:16:56,178
If you practice saying something like, may I not make things worse for myself, during minor difficulties, the phrase may come back to save you in a situation like this.

134
00:16:58,807 --> 00:17:02,392
Patience is also a saviour in threatening situations.

135
00:17:03,754 --> 00:17:09,140
Patience allows you acknowledge aversion for the situation and the wish that it would change.

136
00:17:10,020 --> 00:17:14,665
But both the aversion and the desire for change are encompassed in equanimity.

137
00:17:15,847 --> 00:17:24,698
Phrases like everything in its own time or things are unfolding just as they should strengthen patience.

138
00:17:26,010 --> 00:17:30,115
steadied by morality, resolve, equanimity and patience.

139
00:17:31,017 --> 00:17:36,364
You might then be ready to launch into the flood and find some words to resolve the situation.

140
00:17:39,888 --> 00:17:48,880
Let's finish the story on an optimistic note and presume we make a good enough raft and paddle it energetically enough to get to the far shore.

141
00:17:50,699 --> 00:17:57,711
Whatever way the situation played itself out, we've kept our integrity and somehow got ourselves out of danger.

142
00:17:59,693 --> 00:18:09,430
It might be hard to think of the incident as a spiritual practice, but keep in mind the image of a rickety raft made out of grass and twigs and leaves.

143
00:18:11,413 --> 00:18:13,436
Our practice doesn't have to look pretty.

144
00:18:13,497 --> 00:18:16,942
It just has to get us across the floods.

145
00:18:18,221 --> 00:18:28,454
Although we'd probably be rattled by the whole experience, we've actually done ourselves a lot of good in spiritual terms, avoiding a severe temptation to indulge anger.

146
00:18:30,136 --> 00:18:40,230
Our teacher role has submitted to the demands of the Dhamma, and as a result we would be in a much better position to handle the flood of becoming in future.

147
00:18:43,281 --> 00:18:48,951
Finally, let's look at the flood of ignorance which underlies all the other floods.

148
00:18:50,373 --> 00:18:56,701
Ignorance is a harsh sounding word for something as innocent as not knowing how to be happy.

149
00:18:58,224 --> 00:19:01,169
Perhaps we could call it the flood of confusion.

150
00:19:03,512 --> 00:19:11,684
No matter what we call it, the fact that we don't know how to be happy underlies all our suffering in life.

151
00:19:13,707 --> 00:19:18,714
To traverse this flood we need a raft made out of the Four Noble Truths.

152
00:19:20,457 --> 00:19:33,817
We need to fully understand Dukkha, let go of the desires that cause Dukkha and realize for ourselves there is a state of perfect contentment when we let go of unskillful desire.

153
00:19:36,300 --> 00:19:40,406
To accomplish all of these we need to follow the Eightfold Path.

154
00:19:42,209 --> 00:19:47,273
We paddle our way through this flood in quiet moments when the other floods have subsided.

155
00:19:48,875 --> 00:19:58,105
We may be sitting quietly at home, physically comfortable, fed and watered, not troubled by anything in particular, just relaxing.

156
00:19:59,827 --> 00:20:02,631
But still there's an underlying unease.

157
00:20:04,192 --> 00:20:06,555
After a few moments we get restless.

158
00:20:07,695 --> 00:20:11,220
We want something to fill our minds, get us going again.

159
00:20:12,532 --> 00:20:14,134
This is the flood of ignorance.

160
00:20:15,855 --> 00:20:23,103
Even when all the external conditions for peace and contentment are there, we don't know how to be happy.

161
00:20:25,125 --> 00:20:33,532
We see this very clearly in meditation practice, how the mind keeps creating stories and dramas to fill up the quietness.

162
00:20:35,015 --> 00:20:39,199
Even unhappy stories and bad dramas are preferable to nothing at all.

163
00:20:42,097 --> 00:20:54,109
We also experience the flood of ignorance as we draw near the far shore and have to decide what to do with our raft and it's that aspect of the flood I'd like to focus on tonight.

164
00:20:56,632 --> 00:21:02,738
Suppose we had managed to get our cruise ship together and see Jack and all the other pupils as enlightened beings.

165
00:21:04,099 --> 00:21:11,446
A great wave of love pulls them into our heart and produces some wise words which resolve the crisis.

166
00:21:13,029 --> 00:21:23,501
That wave of love seeps into our geography teaching and the remainder of the class passes like a dream, with everyone, including Jack and his buddies, paying rapt attention.

167
00:21:24,583 --> 00:21:27,746
By the time the class is over, we're walking on air.

168
00:21:29,048 --> 00:21:35,674
We've got through the flood of becoming in great style, but we're still in danger from the flood of ignorance.

169
00:21:37,596 --> 00:21:43,002
When we're walking on air, it's very easy to believe this is the real me

170
00:21:44,417 --> 00:21:52,208
We think our troubles are over, that Jack will never misbehave again, and even if he does, we know how to handle the situation.

171
00:21:53,369 --> 00:21:54,530
Just picture him as the Buddha.

172
00:21:55,192 --> 00:21:56,273
What could be simpler?

173
00:21:58,175 --> 00:22:01,780
This, of course, is to be swept away on the flood of ignorance.

174
00:22:03,123 --> 00:22:11,032
We've identified with the happiness that has come our way, and think we're in control of it, but we'll always be able to summon it at will.

175
00:22:12,261 --> 00:22:17,547
But until we're fully enlightened, our happiness will always depend on conditions.

176
00:22:18,709 --> 00:22:21,151
After a while, we'll come down to earth.

177
00:22:21,872 --> 00:22:32,102
And at the next class, we might be so shocked to find Jack back to his old tricks that we can't muster any metaphor for him at all, never mind picture him as the Buddha.

178
00:22:35,605 --> 00:22:39,450
Let's recap on the Buddha's words on getting to the far shore.

179
00:22:41,792 --> 00:22:43,916
And what should the man do with the raft?

180
00:22:44,917 --> 00:22:51,368
There is the case where the man, having crossed over, would think, How useful this raft has been to me!

181
00:22:52,210 --> 00:23:00,584
For it was in dependence on this raft that, making an effort with my hands and feet, I have crossed over to safety on the far shore.

182
00:23:02,106 --> 00:23:07,075
So we're tempted to hoist the raft on our shoulder and take it with us on our journey.

183
00:23:08,928 --> 00:23:11,652
But according to the Buddha, this isn't wise.

184
00:23:12,953 --> 00:23:15,397
We're to leave our beloved raft behind.

185
00:23:17,080 --> 00:23:23,932
Why don't I, having dragged it on dry land or sinking it in the water, go wherever I like?

186
00:23:25,875 --> 00:23:30,582
In doing this, he would be doing what should be done with the raft.

187
00:23:36,298 --> 00:23:41,930
So we should first reflect on our raft and appreciate how well it has served us.

188
00:23:43,112 --> 00:23:48,561
In this case we would reflect on our ability to picture the pupils as enlightened beings.

189
00:23:49,804 --> 00:23:56,636
Doubtless there'll be a temptation to think, I know how to do this now, I'll always be able to do it.

190
00:23:56,768 --> 00:24:01,032
But that would be to carry the raft on our head as we go on our onward journey.

191
00:24:02,035 --> 00:24:02,895
It's delusional.

192
00:24:04,076 --> 00:24:07,340
We have to rejoice in our raft while letting it go.

193
00:24:10,464 --> 00:24:16,051
Letting go of skillful qualities is one of the major challenges on our spiritual path.

194
00:24:17,753 --> 00:24:25,864
It's quite natural to get attached to metta and states of deep concentration or joy or tranquillity.

195
00:24:27,785 --> 00:24:34,654
Our job, though, is to note these, just as we note physical sensations or any of the hindrances.

196
00:24:36,657 --> 00:24:47,071
It is within that objective knowing of these as transient experiences that we can free ourselves from the dukkha of false identification.

197
00:24:48,294 --> 00:24:52,559
If we don't manage this, the fall from grace can be very sore indeed.

198
00:24:53,619 --> 00:24:57,483
One moment we're light as a feather, loving everyone deeply.

199
00:24:58,605 --> 00:25:08,714
Somehow our hold on this gets broken and we're distraught to find ourselves back as the old me, with all of our petty grievances perfectly intact.

200
00:25:10,057 --> 00:25:17,463
In fact, we're in a worse mood than usual because of having somehow lost our footing on that wonderful far shore.

201
00:25:18,945 --> 00:25:21,248
This can be a very deep shock and sorrow.

202
00:25:24,198 --> 00:25:29,085
One problem is that we often don't know we're attached to something until we lose it.

203
00:25:30,627 --> 00:25:33,571
The post-retreat period is a good teacher in this regard.

204
00:25:34,794 --> 00:25:41,002
For a while we may be walking on air, at peace with the world and even our old enemies.

205
00:25:42,506 --> 00:25:45,430
But somehow we fall back into our old ways.

206
00:25:46,557 --> 00:25:54,710
It can be quite shocking to see how easily we get sucked into these sense pleasures, even though we know they're transient and unsatisfactory.

207
00:25:56,071 --> 00:26:02,261
Worse still, we can be tempted to blame ourselves and everyone around us for our fall from grace.

208
00:26:03,624 --> 00:26:06,067
Even the dog and the goldfish are despicable.

209
00:26:08,478 --> 00:26:26,102
Eventually, of course, things even out and when they do, we will be able to appreciate again the benefits of the retreat, but this time in a more balanced way, knowing that whatever new levels of metta or clarity we might experience, they will come and go.

210
00:26:26,142 --> 00:26:38,298
The first time I really became aware of this was after a three-week retreat in Nepal, which had followed on a pilgrimage around India.

211
00:26:39,832 --> 00:26:47,587
I was walking on air, inspired and confident that I had undergone an enormous transformation for the better.

212
00:26:49,571 --> 00:27:00,674
The exalted state survived the journey back to Delhi, but when the taxi to the airport was over an hour late and no other taxis to be found, it started to quake a bit.

213
00:27:01,954 --> 00:27:05,782
Luckily the plane was even later than my taxi, so I got home all right.

214
00:27:06,704 --> 00:27:10,534
But my first night in my own bed was one of deep distress.

215
00:27:11,556 --> 00:27:13,220
It really felt like bereavement.

216
00:27:14,462 --> 00:27:21,076
I was heartbroken for the loss of that beautiful state of confidence, clarity and inspiration.

217
00:27:24,162 --> 00:27:32,490
Nowadays I try to prepare myself for the fall from grace and to see the post-retreat period as part of the retreat itself.

218
00:27:34,012 --> 00:27:40,299
While on retreat I'm often looking forward to the ending and to relaxing the intensity of practice.

219
00:27:41,641 --> 00:27:49,950
And at first the wide world seems very lovely but sometime later despondency of one form or another descends.

220
00:27:51,009 --> 00:27:59,963
As Sarah, who often does long retreats here at Sati Panya, put it, I can feel worse on retreat, but I know it's all worthwhile.

221
00:28:00,005 --> 00:28:06,755
Whereas at home I can feel much better, but there's a background sense that I'm wasting my life.

222
00:28:08,679 --> 00:28:11,482
That expresses my own sentiments very well.

223
00:28:13,336 --> 00:28:23,612
I nowadays spend time during the end of the retreat acknowledging the deeper levels of peace, kindness or understanding that I've been noticing from time to time.

224
00:28:25,214 --> 00:28:27,157
This is to appreciate the raft.

225
00:28:28,700 --> 00:28:40,018
I then remind myself that these aren't mine, that they depend on conditions like the rule of silence, the schedule, the company of other meditators and so on.

226
00:28:41,432 --> 00:28:57,650
Although this brings grief, it also allows gratitude to flow for these supports and for Bhante's work in establishing Satipaña and guiding us all along, and for all my efforts to practice during the retreat.

227
00:28:57,690 --> 00:29:07,440
During the post-retreat blues, I can then be more compassionate and take care of myself wisely.

228
00:29:09,412 --> 00:29:18,622
Another danger is to neglect practice in the immediate aftermath of a long retreat, to think, I've done enough of that for the moment, I need a break.

229
00:29:20,023 --> 00:29:31,277
To counter this reaction, I arrange to meet up with meditation friends, make a special effort to go to meditation group meetings and to get back into my own daily practice.

230
00:29:32,617 --> 00:29:38,625
The more Dhamma supports I can find in the outside world, the easier it is to get through the blues.

231
00:29:40,494 --> 00:29:48,885
In summary, the post-retreat period gives us practice at letting go of whatever rafts get us through the floods.

232
00:29:51,068 --> 00:29:53,673
Note that the Buddha gives us two options here.

233
00:29:55,355 --> 00:30:01,502
Either we are to sink the raft in water or to drag it onto the beach and leave it there.

234
00:30:03,445 --> 00:30:10,434
My understanding is that we sink our raft in the water when we use it to navigate through the flood of ignorance.

235
00:30:12,727 --> 00:30:14,009
Let's take an example.

236
00:30:16,391 --> 00:30:20,957
Suppose we have used a raft of metta to get us through a flood of views.

237
00:30:23,359 --> 00:30:24,401
We're now at ease.

238
00:30:25,382 --> 00:30:27,444
We can see the other person's point of view.

239
00:30:28,486 --> 00:30:32,029
We see them as a friend and we look back at our little hissy fit.

240
00:30:32,510 --> 00:30:33,991
We can giggle at our pettiness.

241
00:30:35,153 --> 00:30:36,996
The raft has done its job.

242
00:30:38,443 --> 00:30:46,076
So we spend a moment to value our metta practice, being grateful for it, resolving to continue to develop this.

243
00:30:47,799 --> 00:30:50,564
With that, we simply let the whole matter go.

244
00:30:50,584 --> 00:30:55,291
If we were meditating, we would return to the breath.

245
00:30:56,835 --> 00:31:01,583
If we were taking a break in daily life, we would move on to the next task.

246
00:31:03,587 --> 00:31:05,810
That would be to leave the raft on the beach.

247
00:31:06,771 --> 00:31:08,534
A very simple letting go.

248
00:31:08,594 --> 00:31:23,731
Now suppose that as we are reflecting on our metta practice, valuing it, being grateful for it, we find it hard to say goodbye, to let it go.

249
00:31:25,574 --> 00:31:29,358
We then have to work with our attachment to the beautiful state of metta.

250
00:31:31,718 --> 00:31:36,465
We acknowledge whatever emotions show up and let them burn out.

251
00:31:38,930 --> 00:31:41,252
This is to sink our raft in the water.

252
00:31:44,578 --> 00:31:56,156
We are working with the flood of ignorance, seeing more deeply into the second noble truth that desire for the state of metta is causing us to suffer.

253
00:31:59,123 --> 00:32:03,667
We're learning the humbling lesson that goodwill is not ours to own.

254
00:32:05,089 --> 00:32:08,232
It comes and goes depending on conditions.

255
00:32:10,035 --> 00:32:13,878
Ironically, it can make us quite angry to realize that.

256
00:32:15,902 --> 00:32:21,688
It's only with lots of patient effort that we can be persuaded to let the raft sink away.

257
00:32:25,567 --> 00:32:29,291
Related to this, we have the Buddha's last words from the Sutta.

258
00:32:31,154 --> 00:32:40,528
In the same way, monks, I have taught the Dhamma compared to a raft for the purpose of crossing over, not for the purpose of holding on to.

259
00:32:40,587 --> 00:32:51,844
Understanding the Dhamma as taught compared to a raft, you should let go even of Dhammas to say nothing of non-Dhammas.

260
00:32:58,372 --> 00:33:06,721
Just as we let go of Metta or whatever got us across the flood, we also have to let go of whatever Dhamma wisdom we have mustered.

261
00:33:08,403 --> 00:33:10,365
This again is a deep challenge.

262
00:33:11,748 --> 00:33:13,910
We treasure our understanding of the Dhamma.

263
00:33:15,271 --> 00:33:17,515
It represents our only hope of happiness.

264
00:33:18,516 --> 00:33:20,597
So naturally we get attached.

265
00:33:22,621 --> 00:33:24,682
But all attachments bring pain.

266
00:33:26,553 --> 00:33:30,978
It's very painful to have to admit that our understanding is insufficient.

267
00:33:32,398 --> 00:33:34,801
In words, it all sounds so simple.

268
00:33:35,742 --> 00:33:37,144
Desire causes suffering.

269
00:33:37,924 --> 00:33:40,688
Let go of desire and suffering ceases.

270
00:33:42,529 --> 00:33:44,031
We agonize within ourselves.

271
00:33:44,731 --> 00:33:45,794
I know that already.

272
00:33:45,854 --> 00:33:48,135
Why can't I just do it?

273
00:33:48,836 --> 00:33:50,838
It seems such a mystery.

274
00:33:53,114 --> 00:34:07,916
The drill, as we know, is to keep relaxing around the tensions, noting all the protests, the emotions, the confusion, the frustration, until the moment comes when something inside shifts and we're at ease.

275
00:34:08,878 --> 00:34:15,788
We might not be able to put into words what we've learned, but we're no longer quarrelling with ourselves.

276
00:34:16,730 --> 00:34:22,057
We've experienced again that letting go of desire allows suffering to cease.

277
00:34:23,472 --> 00:34:34,860
But oh, the temptation to attach to our new level of clarity, to think, OK, now I know and I won't ever get mixed up again.

278
00:34:34,920 --> 00:34:39,793
And then unwittingly cause ourselves repeated agony.

279
00:34:41,764 --> 00:34:54,425
In this teaching the Buddha emphasizes that we must look on our understanding as part of the raft, to be really grateful that it got us across the flood, but then to let it go.

280
00:34:54,445 --> 00:35:00,715
The attempt to do this will show us our attachment.

281
00:35:04,121 --> 00:35:09,409
As I reflect on any new level of insight, delight will generally emerge.

282
00:35:10,789 --> 00:35:17,175
But in that delight, there's often a streak of pride and my head literally starts swelling.

283
00:35:18,777 --> 00:35:26,746
The discomfort of a swollen head shows me very graphically that, despite my new insight, I've still a long way to go.

284
00:35:26,786 --> 00:35:37,556
There is then the effort to accept this unpalatable fact and make peace with the unenlightened being that I now am.

285
00:35:41,266 --> 00:35:47,833
To help with the process we can bring to mind the pain of attaching to Dhamma understanding.

286
00:35:49,619 --> 00:35:52,170
We experience this in various ways.

287
00:35:53,432 --> 00:35:56,476
One is when we try out a different meditation technique.

288
00:35:57,637 --> 00:35:59,418
At first it's a welcome change.

289
00:36:00,500 --> 00:36:03,643
Then after some time we find it hard to concentrate.

290
00:36:04,284 --> 00:36:08,268
It doesn't seem to let us relax as much as our usual method.

291
00:36:08,288 --> 00:36:11,570
But our warrior spirit compels us to give it another go.

292
00:36:11,610 --> 00:36:17,617
After another aeon of fruitless effort we're confused, angry and frustrated.

293
00:36:17,657 --> 00:36:19,699
We can't catch any thoughts.

294
00:36:19,798 --> 00:36:23,422
They're exploding all over the place and we believe them all.

295
00:36:25,646 --> 00:36:32,934
This turmoil is coming from being attached to views on how to meditate and to our role as competent meditator.

296
00:36:34,494 --> 00:36:38,719
So we have the flood of views criss-crossing with the flood of becoming.

297
00:36:41,041 --> 00:36:44,284
When this happened to me, Bhante's advice was excellent.

298
00:36:45,565 --> 00:36:48,847
Stick with the new technique until the aversion passes.

299
00:36:49,969 --> 00:36:53,072
Then make a rational decision as to which is better for you.

300
00:36:55,161 --> 00:37:02,409
This helped me work through my attachment to the deeply focused form of Mahasi meditation that Bhante encourages.

301
00:37:08,574 --> 00:37:12,659
Another way we can work with this attachment is during Dhamma discussions.

302
00:37:14,882 --> 00:37:20,748
We can get hurt when our opinions are challenged or become afraid to express any views.

303
00:37:22,108 --> 00:37:25,152
Then again we can be delighted when our opinions prevail

304
00:37:26,211 --> 00:37:29,056
but perhaps there's a tinge of pride in that delight.

305
00:37:31,259 --> 00:37:37,648
If we can bear the fear or hurt or pride mindfully, the discussion is actually a very beneficial one.

306
00:37:38,969 --> 00:37:45,157
No matter whether we're learning any new information, we're loosening attachment to our Dhamma views.

307
00:37:47,681 --> 00:37:56,032
Reflecting on the pain of attachment makes us more willing to admit that our understanding isn't perfect, that we need to let go

308
00:37:57,885 --> 00:38:05,193
We need to see ourselves as perpetual students rather than give in to temptation and view ourselves as experts.

309
00:38:06,695 --> 00:38:13,143
Some statements from Arahats reflect a state of continual investigation even after enlightenment.

310
00:38:14,164 --> 00:38:26,998
For example, Meichi Kyo says, I cannot detect a single moment when greed, hatred or delusion have any power over my heart.

311
00:38:28,463 --> 00:38:33,869
This indicates that she is still confirming the Dhamma for herself, still investigating.

312
00:38:37,454 --> 00:38:45,322
To see ourselves as perpetual students rather than experts, we are, in the Buddha's words, letting go of the raft of Dhamma.

313
00:38:46,563 --> 00:38:50,007
But we can love the raft even while we let it go.

314
00:38:50,068 --> 00:38:57,356
We can celebrate and cherish every scrap of understanding that helped us through the flood.

315
00:39:01,369 --> 00:39:11,664
Essentially, this is a mudita practice, celebrating what is ephemeral, transitory, disappearing in front of our eyes.

316
00:39:16,030 --> 00:39:19,414
Before closing, I'd like to go back to the beginning.

317
00:39:21,478 --> 00:39:26,684
The sutta starts out with someone following a path that leads to a perilous shore.

318
00:39:28,184 --> 00:39:33,391
so too our spiritual journey is always leading us to new challenges.

319
00:39:35,333 --> 00:39:41,221
It's interesting that the Buddha doesn't ever suggest turning back and retreating along the path.

320
00:39:42,963 --> 00:39:49,331
This signifies that we can't escape spiritual challenges by keeping to sections of the path we already know.

321
00:39:51,690 --> 00:39:57,840
Supposing you've excellent concentration and can easily access tranquility when you follow your breath.

322
00:39:59,103 --> 00:40:05,452
As the geography teacher under attack from Jack, you could simply let all your attention dwell on your breath.

323
00:40:06,675 --> 00:40:13,445
And so your anger would pass and you could go on with the class, ignoring the tensions caused by the incident.

324
00:40:14,641 --> 00:40:21,447
If you do the same thing whenever the memory of the incident comes up in meditation, then you won't be developing spiritually.

325
00:40:22,409 --> 00:40:29,036
It would be like turning back on the path whenever you come to a perilous shore, and the Buddha isn't recommending that.

326
00:40:30,757 --> 00:40:41,509
Instead, we must take our practice to the edge of our comfort zone, to where we don't know what to do and are flying on a wing into prayer.

327
00:40:42,737 --> 00:40:45,322
That's where we build our raft.

328
00:40:47,266 --> 00:40:49,990
And that's how we learn the Dhamma.

329
00:40:54,057 --> 00:41:07,681
May our Dhamma understanding serve us as a raft until, safe at the far shore, we lay down our raggle-taggle of knowledge and skill and move unburdened onwards.

